The paper deals with algorithms and optimization problems in computer science, specifically in the areas of dynamic programming, graph algorithms, and optimization. The paper's focus on the Knapsack problem and its variations suggests that it belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper's exploration of capacitated dynamic programming and its application to graph algorithms suggests that it also belongs to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. The paper's use of concavity and its exploration of sparsity suggest that it may also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories.
